If additional `z` option is a concern then we can consider enabling it by default like we did for `--mount=type=cache` https://github.com/containers/buildah/pull/4192 but `--mount=type=bind` is different from `--mount=type=cache` since it allows users to select arbitrary path on host and I am not sure if we should do it by default for bind mounts since it will change label secretly by default. 

With docker i think its not needed cause either `SELinux` is not enabled on the VM created by `docker` or it is adding `z` by default, the later case could be incorrect IMO cause it may change SELinux label on host secretly such that user is not aware.

@nalind @rhatdan @containers/buildah-maintainers WDYT ?

@lucacome you may want to check https://github.com/nginx/agent/pull/158

Basically, adding `z` (or `Z` in some cases) to volume flags is a working way to achieve a goal of being able to build the same stuff under docker (using Docker Desktop or just CLI) and podman on various platforms. There are other differences that may arise along the way (like https://github.com/containers/podman/issues/16969), but most of those tend to have easy workarounds.

We are using podman and podman-compose a lot for CI tasks on the same things that also works under docker + docker-compose, and based on collected expertise I wouldn't say that simple `alias docker=podman` will work in 100% cases.
